# Fluff Date: 2026-02-16 11:04:06
overview:<p>The Hammerhands was introduced in 2475 by Achernar BattleMechs as the Federated Suns' second exclusive BattleMech design. After a decade of reviewing complaints about the BattleAxe, Achernar's engineers increased the chassis weight to seventy-five tons while de-rating the engine, replacing the earlier design's troublesome particle projection cannons with a pair of heavy autocannons mounted in each arm. The modifications were extensive enough that Achernar chose to rebrand the design entirely, christening it the Hammerhands in honor of the devastating firepower loaded in each arm.</p><p>The Hammerhands quickly became the Federated Suns' signature military machine, enjoying considerable popularity within the AFFS for decades. Its success proved short-lived, however, as the Terran Hegemony's Warhammer — itself inspired by the Hammerhands and BattleAxe — steadily eclipsed both progenitor designs, eventually driving the Hammerhands into near-obscurity until its revival during the Jihad.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Hammerhands design philosophy centered on solving the BattleAxe's chronic overheating by replacing its particle projection cannons with a pair of Mydron Model B Autocannon/10s, one mounted in each arm. This traded energy weapon dependency for ammunition-based reliability, giving MechWarriors sustained firepower without crippling heat buildup. Backed by ChisComp 38 medium lasers in each arm and a shoulder-mounted Harpoon-6 SRM-6 rack, the weapons platform delivers punishing volleys at both medium and close range.</p><p>The seventy-five-ton chassis carries StarGuard III armor in respectable quantities, though protection remains secondary to firepower in the design's priorities. Rawlings 50 jump jets provide ninety meters of jump capability, an unusual feature for a heavy 'Mech of the Age of War era that many Federated Suns pilots were slow to embrace. Ground speed suffers at only fifty-four kilometers per hour, making the Hammerhands among the slower designs in its weight class.</p><p>The autocannon-heavy loadout created a favorable damage-to-heat ratio that endeared it to generations of Davion MechWarriors and sparked the Federated Suns' enduring fascination with ballistic weaponry. The barrel-shrouded arm mounts also allow effective physical combat without compromising the primary weapons.</p>

deployment:<p>This specialized variant was fielded by the AFFS Prince's Champion on Royal during the Second Hidden War, the covert conflict between the Federated Suns and the Draconis Combine waged beneath the Star League's notice. The modification replaces the standard autocannons with a pair of LB 10-X autocannons capable of firing both solid shot and cluster rounds for increased versatility. The jump jets are removed to free tonnage for three additional heat sinks and two extra tons of armor, creating a more durable platform suited to sustained engagements.</p>

history:<p>The Hammerhands emerged from Achernar BattleMechs in 2475 as a direct response to the failures of the BattleAxe, the Federated Suns' first exclusive BattleMech design. Where the BattleAxe had been plagued by chronic overheating from its particle projection cannons, the Hammerhands traded those weapons for Mydron Model B autocannons, a change that proved enormously popular with Davion MechWarriors. The design quickly became the chosen BattleMech of the Federated Suns military, spreading through the AFFS so rapidly that the Terran Hegemony took notice.</p><p>The Hegemony ultimately drew on both the Hammerhands and the BattleAxe as inspiration when StarCorps Industries created the Warhammer in 2515. Achernar fiercely protested this appropriation of their flagship designs, but the Warhammer proved superior in virtually every measurable respect. Improved secondary weapons, better heat management, and higher ground speed combined to render the Hammerhands obsolete. In repeated confrontations between the two designs, the Warhammer prevailed decisively, and the Hammerhands earned the derisive nickname the "poor man's Warhammer." Both the Hammerhands and BattleAxe gradually faded from frontline service.</p><p>Even as the design disappeared from active inventories, the autocannons it had championed endured. The Mydron Corporation's prominence, built on the Hammerhands' success, helped establish the autocannon as the Federated Suns' weapon of choice. Military media highlighted the weapons' favorable damage-to-heat ratio, and a generation of cadets grew up seeking autocannon-equipped 'Mechs, cementing a doctrinal preference that would persist for centuries. Mydron would eventually locate many of its factories in the Hegemony, only to have them destroyed in the Amaris Coup.</p><p>The Hammerhands' revival came during the Jihad, when the Federated Suns military-industrial complex resurrected several Age of War designs. Achernar BattleMechs on New Avalon and Hessen IndustrialWorks on New Hessen both restarted production lines, initially fielding updated versions of the venerable design for the Armed Forces of the Federated Suns. The modernized variants incorporated advanced technologies including C3 networking, rotary autocannons, and triple-strength myomer, transforming the ancient chassis into a credible Jihad-era combatant. Production of the HMH-6D and HMH-6E continued well beyond the Jihad, with Achernar maintaining active lines into the ilClan era.</p>

